data.content:
Yes — use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType`, which both verifies the type and gives a clear failure message (instead of an `InvalidCastException`):

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void Create_ReturnsCorrectHandler()
{
    var factory = new HandlerFactory();
    var result = factory.Create("email");

    Assert.IsInstanceOfType<EmailHandler>(result);
    var handler = (EmailHandler)result;
    Assert.AreEqual("email", handler.Type);
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- A wrong type produces a descriptive test failure, not a runtime `InvalidCastException`
- `IsInstanceOfType<T>` (MSTest v3+) is generic and compile-time safe
- On older MSTest, use `Assert.IsInstanceOfType(result, typeof(EmailHandler))`
